fields.params:
{"why_md_fmt":"Poverty has a cascading negative effect on almost all health determinants and outcomes. Impoverished households are most affected by:

- Limited access to healthcare
- Limited access to nutritional food
- Negative societal perception
- Fundamentally limited opportunity

These effects lead impoverished households to experience:

- Higher rates of physical illness and injury
- Higher rates of stress and physiological poor health
- A lower quality of life
- A lower life expectancy
","references":[{"date":"Dec 2013","publisher":"U.S. Census Bureau","link":"http://www.census.gov/hhes/www/poverty/about/overview/measure.html","title":"How the Census Bureau Measures Poverty"},{"date":"2003","publisher":"WHO","link":"http://www.euro.who.int/__data/assets/pdf_file/0005/98438/e81384.pdf","title":"The Solid Facts, Second Edition"},{"date":"1999","publisher":"International Journal of Health Services","link":"http://individual.utoronto.ca/cmuntaner/publications/1990/1999MuntanerIntJHealthServ1.pdf","title":"Social Inequalities and Their Effect on Health and Well-Being"},{"date":"2014","publisher":"U.S. Department of Health and Human Services","link":"http://www.healthypeople.gov/2020/topicsobjectives2020/overview.aspx?topicid=39","title":"Social Determinants of Health"},{"date":"2013","publisher":"CDC","link":"http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/other/su6203.pdf","title":"CDC Health Disparities and Inequalities Report"}],"stats":{"average":0.166,"std_dev":0.118383,"better_sign":-1},"score_md_fmt":"In **{boundary}**, **{value}** of people live in a household where the income is below the poverty level, versus **{average}** in {domain}. {"why_md_fmt":"Less access to employment and a longer commute time to work has a generally negative effect on population health. Areas with limited access to employment are most affected by:

- Higher commute time
- Higher annual transportation costs
- Reduced free time
- Higher risk of transportation-related injury

These effects can lead people to experience higher rates of stree and physiological poor health.
","stats":{"average":0.082964,"std_dev":0.059340889,"better_sign":-1},"score_md_fmt":"In **{boundary}**, **{value}** of workers have a long commute time, versus **{average}** in {domain}. fields.params:
{"why_md_fmt":" Higher rates of unemployment in an area are likely to have a negative effect on health in that area. Areas with higher rates of unemployment are most affected by:

- Lower lifetime income
- Lack of employer-provided health care
- Reduced human and societal capital

These effects lead areas with higher rates of unemployment to experience:

- Higher rates of poverty
- Higher rates of stress and physiological poor health
- Reduced life expectancy
- Reduced quality of life
","references":[{"date":"Mar 2013","publisher":"Robert Wood Johnson Foundation","link":"http://www.rwjf.org/content/dam/farm/reports/issue_briefs/2013/rwjf403360","title":"How Does Employment - or Unemployment - Affect Health?"},{"date":"July 2013","publisher":"Urban Institute","link":"http://www.urban.org/uploadedpdf/412887-consequences-of-long-term-unemployment.pdf","title":"Consequences of Long-Term Unemployment"},{"date":"1999","publisher":"International Journal of Health Services","link":"http://individual.utoronto.ca/cmuntaner/publications/1990/1999MuntanerIntJHealthServ1.pdf","title":"Social Inequalities and Their Effect on Health and Well-Being"}],"stats":{"average":0.04193,"std_dev":0.0266,"better_sign":-1},"score_md_fmt":"In **{boundary}**, **{value}** of people are searching for employment but unable to find a job, versus **{average}** in {domain}. fields.params:
{"why_md_fmt":"Higher rates of high school graduation indicate a higher level of educational attainment. Populations with higher levels of educational attainment can be expected to report better health than populations with lower levels of educational attainment. This is because a well educated population is more likely to:

- Be financially stable
- Avoid certain risk factors

Therefore, areas where more of the population has graduated high school are more likely to experience:

- Lower rates of poverty
- Higher life expectancy
- Lower rates of injury and illness
- A higher quality of life
","references":[{"date":"Mar 2007","publisher":"National Bureau of Economic Research","link":"http://www.nber.org/digest/mar07/w12352.html","title":"The Effects of Education on Health"}],"stats":{"average":0.861836,"std_dev":0.096739,"better_sign":1},"score_md_fmt":"In **{boundary}**, **{value}** of people 25 and older have graduated from high school, versus **{average}** in {domain}.
